of power wash over him,

152
00:10:56,807 --> 00:10:58,346
just like in his dreams.

153
00:10:58,346 --> 00:10:59,611
- Oh.

154
00:10:59,611 --> 00:11:01,776
- I'm flying, I'm flying.

155
00:11:01,776 --> 00:11:03,105
Really, I'm flying.

156
00:11:03,105 --> 00:11:05,688
- That's good, the little twit.

157
00:11:09,067 --> 00:11:10,384
- I think he's all right.

158
00:11:10,384 --> 00:11:11,801
He's in his room.

159
00:11:13,466 --> 00:11:14,299
- Oh.

160
00:11:19,214 --> 00:11:21,339
Have I not been listening?

161
00:11:21,339 --> 00:11:24,166
- I know you love your children.

162
00:11:24,166 --> 00:11:26,583
But sometimes, you see Joseph

163
00:11:28,462 --> 00:11:32,629
and hear Joseph a little more
than you hear the others.

164
00:11:33,501 --> 00:11:37,668
- How can I not, I mean, see
him at least differently?

165
00:11:38,621 --> 00:11:40,285
And Joseph is our child.

166
00:11:40,285 --> 00:11:42,423
He's the only child of our marriage.

167
00:11:42,423 --> 00:11:44,267
- They're all our children.

168
00:11:44,267 --> 00:11:48,250
And blood related or
not, I'm their mother.

169
00:11:48,250 --> 00:11:49,833
Joseph is our gift.

170
00:11:51,003 --> 00:11:51,836
- Oh.

171
00:11:54,253 --> 00:11:56,279
I love them all.

172
00:11:56,279 --> 00:11:57,562
I do, I love them all.

173
00:11:57,562 --> 00:11:58,729
- I know that.

174
00:12:02,624 --> 00:12:04,432
Do you think of her?

175
00:12:04,432 --> 00:12:05,739
- [Jacob] Sometimes.

176
00:12:05,739 --> 00:12:09,268
- She gave you six wonderful sons.

177
00:12:09,268 --> 00:12:12,185
And she gave you a lovely daughter.

178
00:12:16,288 --> 00:12:18,371
If you had another child,

179
00:12:19,393 --> 00:12:21,518
what would you want?

180
00:12:21,518 --> 00:12:23,654
Another son or another daughter?

181
00:12:23,654 --> 00:12:25,904
(laughing)

182
00:12:26,817 --> 00:12:28,322
- I think we're getting a little too old

183
00:12:28,322 --> 00:12:30,322
for that sorta nonsense.

184
00:12:34,411 --> 00:12:35,411
- We're not.

185
00:12:37,828 --> 00:12:39,281
- We're not?

186
00:12:39,281 --> 00:12:41,698
(chattering)

187
00:12:46,925 --> 00:12:48,626
- Well, it's taken us a couple of months,

188
00:12:48,626 --> 00:12:51,987
but I think our coffee problem
is finally solved, you guys.

189
00:12:51,987 --> 00:12:54,170
- You're sure these figures are right?

190
00:12:54,170 --> 00:12:55,836
- Ash, listen to me.

191
00:12:55,836 --> 00:12:58,367
Father expected us to need
money for the next season.

192
00:12:58,367 --> 00:13:00,211
- Yeah, well, I had
intended to show Father

193
00:13:00,211 --> 00:13:03,533
that I could increase our profits.

194
00:13:03,533 --> 00:13:05,118
- You know, he's right, Ash.

195
00:13:05,118 --> 00:13:06,221
It's not your fault.

196
00:13:06,221 --> 00:13:09,562
- Ash, look, remember Simon's suggestion?

197
00:13:09,562 --> 00:13:11,892
He and Justin, they're
working it out right now.

198
00:13:11,892 --> 00:13:13,634
Right now, as we speak.

199
00:13:13,634 --> 00:13:15,571
That's gonna help us out a lot.

200
00:13:15,571 --> 00:13:19,665
- Is this something that you
guys have gone over with Dad?

201
00:13:19,665 --> 00:13:22,498
(horn honking)

202
00:13:22,498 --> 00:13:23,415
- Joe, Joe.

203
00:13:24,727 --> 00:13:28,808
When Father established this
business, labor was cheap.

204
00:13:28,808 --> 00:13:30,352
Now, with the laws and the unions,

205
00:13:30,352 --> 00:13:32,477
our competitors are just
blowing us out of the water.

206
00:13:32,477 --> 00:13:34,031
What are we gonna do?

207
00:13:34,031 --> 00:13:36,192
- Father just doesn't
understand today's market.

208
00:13:36,192 --> 00:13:39,319
The competition, you know,
it's just tougher out there.

209
00:13:39,319 --> 00:13:42,211
- So, what is that you guys plan to do?

210
00:13:42,211 --> 00:13:46,360
- Okay, see, it's the cost
of labor that's killing us.

211
00:13:46,360 --> 00:13:50,377
So that's the one area that
we can probably cut back on.

212
00:13:50,377 --> 00:13:54,727
- You can't cut pay and
benefits, you can't do that.

213
00:13:54,727 --> 00:13:55,894
- Not exactly.

214
00:13:56,945 --> 00:13:59,609
It would be having to let some people go.

215
00:13:59,609 --> 00:14:02,523
You're just contracting
it out to somebody else.

216
00:14:02,523 --> 00:14:04,137
- Wait a minute.

217
00:14:04,137 --> 00:14:06,767
Are you talking about using sweatshops?

218
00:14:06,767 --> 00:14:09,826
- Look, I've arranged it with Justin.

219
00:14:09,826 --> 00:14:10,928
He can arrange the whole thing

220
00:14:10,928 --> 00:14:13,134
so we won't be legally connected.

221
00:14:13,134 --> 00:14:15,362
- That's not the point, and you know it.

222
00:14:15,362 --> 00:14:18,230
Ash, you can't agree to this.

223
00:14:18,230 --> 00:14:22,248
- Grant says these places,
they're not as bad as reported.

224
00:14:22,248 --> 00:14:24,036
- Of course they are.

225
00:14:24,036 --> 00:14:25,510
Why do you think they stay underground?

226
00:14:25,510 --> 00:14:27,871
Because they're such nice places to work?

227
00:14:27,871 --> 00:14:30,132
Dad will never agree to
this, and you know it.

228
00:14:30,132 --> 00:14:33,383
- Joe, he can't stop
what he don't know about.

229
00:14:33,383 --> 00:14:35,780
Besides, these shops are right
here in the United States.

230
00:14:35,780 --> 00:14:38,918
They're not in some third-world slum.

231
00:14:38,918 --> 00:14:40,370
Right here.

232
00:14:40,370 --> 00:14:42,953
- That doesn't change anything.

233
00:14:44,139 --> 00:14:45,962
- I'm not gonna risk losing
this company that it took

234
00:14:45,962 --> 00:14:49,031
Dad a lifetime to build, what about you?

235
00:14:49,031 --> 00:14:53,184
- This is the future
of our family business.

236
00:14:53,184 --> 00:14:54,229
- Yeah.

237
00:14:54,229 --> 00:14:55,622
- But the costs.

238
00:14:55,622 --> 00:14:58,289
- Joe, sometimes things do cost.

239
00:14:59,921 --> 00:15:04,138
But in this world, you gotta
protect your own first.

240
00:15:04,138 --> 00:15:04,971
- So it's,

241
00:15:05,861 --> 00:15:07,557
it's us or them?

242
00:15:07,557 --> 00:15:10,765
- I'm not gonna argue ethics
and morals with you, Joe.

243
00:15:10,765 --> 00:15:12,700
This is my decision,

244
00:15:12,700 --> 00:15:15,893
and there's no reason
to involve Dad in it.

245
00:15:15,893 --> 00:15:19,136
- Oh no, you will not do this thing.

246
00:15:19,136 --> 00:15:20,670
- It was just an idea, Dad.

247
00:15:20,670 --> 00:15:21,918
Joseph had no right.

248
00:15:21,918 --> 00:15:25,291
- He had every right, every right,

249
00:15:25,291 --> 00:15:28,194
and he was man enough
to do the right thing.

250
00:15:28,194 --> 00:15:31,437
- We were thinking of
the business, of you.

251
00:15:31,437 --> 00:15:33,104
- Thinking about me?

252
00:15:34,237 --> 00:15:38,120
I worked in a sweatshop when I was a kid.

253
00:15:38,120 --> 00:15:40,997
Three years of my life, I slaved.

254
00:15:40,997 --> 00:15:43,495
For scum who had the gall to tell me

255
00:15:43,495 --> 00:15:45,957
that they were doing me
a favor, letting me work

256
00:15:45,957 --> 00:15:49,790
in their stinking shop
for 15, 16 hours a day.

257
00:15:52,662 --> 00:15:55,950
You dare tell me that I raised sons

258
00:15:55,950 --> 00:15:59,425
who would do what those
dregs of humanity did to me?

259
00:15:59,425 --> 00:16:01,092
- I'm sorry, Father.

260
00:16:02,616 --> 00:16:05,393
- I want everybody at the house tonight.

261
00:16:05,393 --> 00:16:07,643
Six o'clock, no exceptions.

262
00:16:08,551 --> 00:16:11,301
(birds chirping)

263
00:16:13,031 --> 00:16:15,707
- I planned to present
this with a little bit

264
00:16:15,707 --> 00:16:19,790
more pomp and circumstance
on Sunday dinner, but.

265
00:16:25,633 --> 00:16:26,466
Try it on.

